0.body: Dobby is a CLI for developers used to automate common tasks workflows. Things like transitioning issues, creating and merging branches, creating pull requests, bumping versions, tagging... anything that is a repetitive, time consuming task in your development cycle, this tool is made to speed up.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: Basically you create a file called dobby.toml in your project directory which defines some workflows. The format of this file is described in the chapter on config , the key piece to which is the workflows array. For a full example of a dobby.toml, check out the file for this project! Once you've got a config set up, you just run this program (dobby if you installed normally via cargo). That will prompt you to select one of your configured workflows. Do that and you're off to the races!
1.title: How it Works

10.body:
[[workflows]]
name = "First Workflow"
# Details here [[workflows]]
name = "Second Workflow"
# Details here [jira]
# Jira config here [github]
# GitHub config here When you first start dobby, you will be asked to select a workflow to run. In the above example, this would look something like: ? Select a workflow
> First Workflow Second Workflow You can use your arrow keys to then select an option to run. The > symbol indicates which workflow is selected. Pressing the Enter key on your keyboard will run the workflow.
10.title: Example

11.body: Workflows for details on defining entries to the [[workflows]] array Jira for details on defining [jira] GitHub for details on defining [github]
11.title: See Also

12.body: A workflow is the entrypoint to doing work with Dobby. Once you start running dobby you must immediately select a workflow (by name) to be executed. Each workflow is defined in the [[workflows]] array in your dobby.toml file. Each entry contains a name attribute which is how the workflow will be displayed when running dobby. There is also an array of steps declared as [[workflows.steps]] which define the individual actions to take.
12.title: Workflow

13.body:
# dobby.toml [[workflows]]
name = "My First Workflow" [[workflows.steps]] # First step details here [[workflows.steps]] # second step details here
13.title: Example

14.body: Step for details on how each [[workflows.steps]] is defined.
14.title: See Also

15.body:
A step is the atomic unit of work that Dobby operates on. In a workflow , steps will be executed sequentially until one fails or all steps are completed. In it's simplest form, a step is declared in a workflow like this: [[workflows]]
name = "My Workflow" [[workflows.steps]] type = "AStepType" more_info = "Something" Where type matches one of the available steps listed below. Some steps also can take additional parameters in config, those go right underneath type like more_info above.
15.title: Step

16.body: SelectJiraIssue TransitionJiraIssue SelectGitHubIssue SelectIssueFromBranch SwitchBranches RebaseBranch BumpVersion Command UpdateProjectFromCommits
16.title: Available Steps

17.body: Search for Jira issues by status and display the list of them in the terminal. User is allowed to select one issue which will then change the workflow's state to IssueSelected .
17.title: SelectJiraIssue

18.body: This step will fail if any of the following are true: The state is already in IssueSelected before it executes. Dobby cannot communicate with the configured Jira URL . User does not select an issue (e.g. by pressing Esc). There is no Jira config set.
18.title: Errors

2.body: More detail on everything this program can do can be found by digging into config but here's a rough (incomplete) summary: Select issues from Jira or GitHub to work on, transition and create branches from them. Do some basic git commands like switching branches or rebasing. Bump the version of your project using semantic rules. Bump your version AND generate a Changelog entry from conventional commits. Do whatever you want by running arbitrary shell commands and substituting data from the project!
2.title: Features

20.body: Transition a Jira issue to a new status.
20.title: TransitionJiraIssue Step

21.body: This step will fail when any of the following are true: The workflow is not yet in IssueSelected state. Cannot communicate with Jira. The configured status is invalid for the issue.
21.title: Errors

[[workflows]]
name = "Start some work" [[workflows.steps]] type = "SelectJiraIssue" status = "Backlog" [[workflows.steps]] type = "TransitionJiraIssue" status = "In Progress"

24.body: This step will fail if any of the following are true: The workflow is already in IssueSelected state before it executes. Dobby cannot communicate with GitHub. There is no GitHub config set. User does not select an issue.

26.body: Attempt to parse issue info from the current branch name and change the workflow's state to IssueSelected .
26.title: SelectIssueFromBranch step

27.body: This step will fail if the current git branch cannot be determined or the name of that branch does not match the expected format. This is only intended to be used on branches which were created using the SwitchBranches step.

[[workflows]]
name = "Finish some work" [[workflows.steps]] type = "SelectIssueFromBranch" [[workflows.steps]] type = "TransitionJiraIssue" status = "QA"

29.body: Uses the name of the currently selected issue to checkout an existing or create a new branch for development. If an existing branch is not found, the user will be prompted to select an existing local branch to base the new branch off of. Remote branches are not shown.
29.title: SwitchBranches step

3.body: You define a config file named dobby.toml which has some metadata (e.g. Jira details) about your project, as well as a set of defined workflows . Each workflow consists of a series of steps that will execute in order, stopping if any step fails. Steps can affect the state of the workflow. Some steps require that the workflow be in a specific state before they will work.
3.title: Concepts

30.body: This step fails if any of the following are true. Workflow is not in IssueSelected state. Current directory is not a Git repository There is uncommitted work on the current branch. You must manually stash or commit any changes before performing this step.
30.title: Errors

31.body:
[[workflows]]
name = "Start some work" [[workflows.steps]] type = "SelectJiraIssue" status = "Backlog" [[workflows.steps]] type = "SwitchBranches"
31.title: Example

32.body: Rebase the current branch onto the branch defined by to.
32.title: RebaseBranch step

33.body: Fails if any of the following are true: The current directory is not a Git repository. The to branch cannot be found locally (does not check remotes). The repo is not on the tip of a branch (e.g. detached HEAD) Rebase fails (e.g. not a clean working tree)
33.title: Errors

35.body: Bump the version of the project in any supported formats found using a Semantic Versioning rule.
35.title: BumpVersion step

36.body: These are the types of files that this step knows how to search for a semantic version and bump. Dobby currently will only search the current directory for these files. Cargo.toml for Rust projects pyproject.toml for Python projects (using Poetry's metadata ) package.json for Node projects
36.title: Supported Formats

37.body:
[[workflows.steps]]
type = "BumpVersion"
rule = "Pre"
value = "rc" Where rule defines the Semantic Versioning rule to use and value is optional depending on the rule.
37.title: Example

39.body: Increment the Major component of the semantic version and reset all other components (e.g. 1.2.3-rc.4 -> 2.0.0).
39.title: Major

40.body: Increment the Minor component of the semantic version and reset all lesser components (e.g. 1.2.3-rc.4 -> 1.3.0 ).
40.title: Minor

41.body: Increment the Patch component of the semantic version and reset all lesser components (e.g. 1.2.3-rc.4 -> 1.2.4).
41.title: Patch

42.body: Increment the pre-release component of the semantic version or add it if missing. You must also provide a value parameter to this rule which will determine the pre-release string used. For example, running this rule with the value "rc" would change "1.2.3-rc.4" to "1.2.3-rc.5" or "1.2.3" to "1.2.3-rc.0".
42.title: Pre

43.body: Remove the pre-release component of the semantic version (e.g. 1.2.3-rc.4 -> 1.2.3).
43.title: Release

44.body: This step will fail if any of the following are true: A malformed version string is found while attempting to bump.
44.title: Errors

45.body: Run a command in your current shell after optionally replacing some variables. This step is here to cover the infinite things you might want to do that Dobby does not yet know how to do itself. If you have a lot of these steps or a complex command, we recommend you write a script in something like Bash or Python, then simply call that script with a command.
45.title: Command step

46.body:
If the current version for your project is "1.0.0", the following workflow step will run git tag v.1.0.0 in your current shell. [[workflows.steps]]
type = "Command"
command = "git tag v.version"
variables = {"version" = "Version"}
46.title: Example

47.body: The variables attribute of this step is an object where the key is the string you wish to substitute and the value is one of the available variables listed below. take care when selecting a key to replace as any matching string that is found will be replaced. The order of this replacement is not guaranteed, so it is also possible for multiple variables to conflict with one another.
47.title: Variables

48.body: Version will attempt to parse the project version using the same method as the BumpVersion step and substitute that string. It will select the first version found in any of the supported file names / formats to use for substitution. If no version can be found and parsed, this step will fail. IssueBranch will provide the same branch name that the SwitchBranches step would produce. Your workflow must be in the IssueSelected state before calling a Command step with this variable or the step will fail.
48.title: Available Variables

49.body: This will look through all commits since the last tag and parse any Conventional Commits it finds. It will then bump the project version (depending on the Semantic Versioning rule determined from the commits) and add a new Changelog entry using the Keep A Changelog format.
49.title: UpdateProjectFromCommits step

5.body: Dobby is written in Rust and published on crates.io which means it can therefore be installed by: Installing cargo via Rustup Running cargo install dobby
5.title: Install via Cargo (Recommended)

50.body: The CHANGELOG format is pretty strict, it needs to have at least one version already in it and every version needs to be a level 2 header (## 1.0.0). Only three sections will be added to the new version, ### Breaking Changes for anything that conventional commits have marked as breaking, ### Fixes for anything called fix:, and ### Features for anything with feat: . Any other commits (conventional or not) will be left out. A new version will always be generated though, even if there are no changes to record.
50.title: Limitations

51.body: The reasons this can fail: If there is no previous tag to base changes off of. There is no CHANGELOG.md file in the working directory to update. The version could not be bumped for some reason.
51.title: Errors

# dobby.toml [jira]
url = "https://mysite.atlassian.net"
project = "PRJ" # where an example issue would be PRJ-123 The first time you use a step which requires this config, you will be prompted to generate a Jira API token so Dobby can perform actions on you behalf.

repo = "dobby" The first time you use a step which requires this config, you will be prompted to generate a GitHub API token so Dobby can perform actions on you behalf.
55.title: Example

56.body: Throughout the course of a workflow , Dobby will often have to remember some information from previous steps to use in future steps. This is done using an internal State. All workflows start in the Initial state and may transition between a states depending on the steps that are run. For example, the SelectJiraIssue step will transition the workflow to the IssueSelected state.
56.title: State

58.body: The starting state for all workflows, contains some config information only.
58.title: Initial State

59.body: This state indicates that work is being done against an issue in some project management platform. Currently the supported platforms are GitHub and Jira. Any step which requires this state must be proceeded by a step which triggers this state.
59.title: IssueSelected State
